            "Opcodes/SectorStarbaseRequestTests.cs JobTerminal_DoesNotBreakConnection_RequestTimeStillRoundTrips — client sends a canonical 9-byte StarbaseRequest payload {int32 PlayerID=0; int32 StarbaseID=0; byte Action=6} on the sector connection after STAGE handshake completes. Action=6 selects the Job-Terminal-open branch (server/src/PlayerConnection.cpp:9928), the leanest read-only sub-action; the handler calls SectorManager::GetJobList and conditionally emits 0x0093 JOB_LIST when jobs exist. Sector 10151's seed has no job rows so the handler silently returns — no direct reply, per CLAUDE.md we don't fabricate one. Test is a survival probe: send STARBASE_REQUEST, send REQUEST_TIME, assert CLIENT_SET_TIME echoes our sentinel tick. Catches: (a) PacketStructures.h StarbaseRequest long→int32_t regression (would grow struct to 17B; Action would read from offset 16 instead of 8, past end of 9B payload into garbage — random action routes risk LaunchIntoSpace on a docked character); (b) proxy default-case ForwardClientOpcode dropping the opcode (0x004E is not explicitly listed in proxy/ClientToServer_linux_stubs.cpp); (c) SectorManager::GetJobList null-deref or buffer overrun; (d) dispatcher mis-route to a different handler. Per CLAUDE.md server-integrity: the wire shape is exactly what retail Win32 client emits when user clicks the Job Terminal NPC."),
        new TestedOpcode(0x0057, "SKILL_UP",
            "Opcodes/SectorSkillUpTests.cs SkillUp_OnUntrainedSkill_DoesNotBreakConnection_RequestTimeStillRoundTrips — client sends a canonical 10-byte SkillAction payload {int32 GameID=0; int SkillPoints=0; int16 SkillID=29} on the sector connection after STAGE handshake completes. SkillID=29 is SKILL_JENQUAI_CULTURE — the seeded skills table has warrior_max_level=-1 for that row, so the per-profession init loop in PlayerSaves::LoadPlayer (server/src/PlayerSaves.cpp:609-647) skips the entry and RPGInfo.Skills.Skill[29] stays at AuxSkill::Init defaults (Level=0, MaxSkillLevel=0, Availability[3]=0). Player::HandleSkillAction (server/src/PlayerSkills.cpp:97-106) trips the very first early-return guard (SkillLevel == SkillMaxLevel where 0==0). No DB write, no AuxPlayer/AuxShip refresh, no direct reply — the retail server doesn't emit one on this branch either, and CLAUDE.md forbids fabricating. Test is a survival probe: send SKILL_UP, send REQUEST_TIME, assert CLIENT_SET_TIME echoes our sentinel tick. **Trap walked into and documented in plans/99-decisions-log.md 2026-05-25**: the dispatcher reads through the AuxSkills wrapper (AuxSkill Skill[64], AuxSkills.h:86) not the raw _Skills::Skill[170] data array, so any SkillID >= 64 reads past the wrapper-array end into Player memory and crashes the sector thread on the garbage Data-pointer deref in GetAvailability. Earlier draft sent SkillID=169 and faulted (docker RestartCount jumped). Catches: (a) PacketStructures.h SkillAction long-revert regression (currently `{int32_t GameID; int SkillPoints; short SkillID}` = 10B canonical; if anyone changes `int SkillPoints` to `long SkillPoints` the struct grows to 14B on Linux x86_64 — SkillID would read from byte 12 past end of 10B payload into undefined memory); (b) proxy default-case ForwardClientOpcode dropping the opcode (0x0057 is not explicitly listed in proxy/ClientToServer_linux_stubs.cpp); (c) AuxSkills::Init loop-bound shrinking below 30 (SkillID=29 sits inside the current <64 bound, but a regression to <32 would crash on Jenquai-Culture too); (d) m_Mutex deadlock if a regression moves the lock above the early-return guards. Per CLAUDE.md server-integrity: the wire shape is exactly what retail Win32 client emits when user clicks the \"+\" on a skill in the skill tree."),
        new TestedOpcode(0x005A, "VERB_REQUEST",
            "Opcodes/SectorVerbRequestTests.cs VerbRequest_OnNonMatchingSubject_DoesNotBreakConnection_RequestTimeStillRoundTrips — client sends a canonical 12-byte VerbRequest payload {int32 SubjectID=0; int32 ObjectID=0; int32 Action=1} on the sector connection after STAGE handshake completes. Player::HandleVerbRequest (server/src/PlayerConnection.cpp:3547) ntohl-decodes SubjectID then checks `subject_id == GameID() && pkt->Action == 1`; with SubjectID=0 and the player's actual GameID being non-zero (assigned by SaveManager during character creation), the equality check fails and the handler returns silently — no UpdateVerbs call, no 0x005C VERB_UPDATE reply. Test is a survival probe: send VERB_REQUEST, send REQUEST_TIME, assert CLIENT_SET_TIME echoes our sentinel tick. Catches: (a) PacketStructures.h VerbRequest long-revert regression (currently 3× int32_t = 12B canonical; if any field is widened to `long` on Linux x86_64 the struct grows and the Action field reads from the wrong offset, garbage-comparing against the GameID guard); (b) proxy default-case ForwardClientOpcode dropping the opcode (0x005A is not explicitly listed in proxy/ClientToServer_linux_stubs.cpp); (c) dispatcher mis-route at server/src/PlayerConnection.cpp:507 (hand-maintained ~200-entry switch); (d) ntohl/htonl byte-order flip on the SubjectID/ObjectID fields (0 is a byte-order fixed point so the equality test result is invariant under flip — but a non-zero garbage value past struct end would suddenly become non-zero on the wrong byte ordering). Per CLAUDE.md server-integrity: the silent-no-op on SubjectID mismatch is exactly the retail server's behaviour; we are not making it accept any new input shape, only exercising the dispatch + struct read path with a payload that walks the silent branch."),
